WEBVTT

00:01.701 --> 00:04.169
An ancient artifact
lost at sea...

00:04.171 --> 00:05.637
♪♪

00:05.639 --> 00:09.508
It was unlike anything
he had ever seen before.

00:09.510 --> 00:12.444
...the incredible tale
behind the real Peter Rabbit...

00:12.446 --> 00:16.248
She knew she had something good,
but she kept getting rejections.

00:16.250 --> 00:18.150
♪♪

00:18.152 --> 00:21.153
...and a bizarre battle
sparks a new sport.

00:21.155 --> 00:24.790
This was the moment
to put his plan into action.

00:24.792 --> 00:26.859
[ Indistinct shouting ]

00:26.861 --> 00:30.095
These are the mysteries
at the museum.

00:30.097 --> 00:33.132
♪♪

00:34.668 --> 00:38.270
On a clear day in Fairbanks,
Alaska, it's possible to glimpse

00:38.272 --> 00:41.874
North America's highest peak,
Denali.

00:41.876 --> 00:45.077
And in the winter months,
the city also offers

00:45.079 --> 00:47.946
spectacular views
of the northern lights.

00:47.948 --> 00:49.815
Honoring the history
and traditions

00:49.817 --> 00:52.084
of the nation's largest state

00:52.086 --> 00:54.953
is the University of Alaska
Museum of the North.

00:54.955 --> 00:57.222
♪♪

00:57.224 --> 01:02.026
Among the 1.5 million specimens
housed here

01:02.028 --> 01:06.031
is a mummified bison
dating back to the last ice age,

01:06.033 --> 01:09.734
tusks that once belonged
to a woolly mammoth,

01:09.736 --> 01:11.503
and the largest nuggets

01:11.505 --> 01:14.373
found during
the Alaskan Gold Rush of 1899.

01:14.375 --> 01:16.040
♪♪

01:16.042 --> 01:19.311
But among these marvels
of the natural world

01:19.313 --> 01:21.780
is an unassuming man-made tool.

01:21.782 --> 01:24.516
WEATHERFORD: The artifact
measures five inches across

01:24.518 --> 01:26.018
and is circular in shape.

01:26.020 --> 01:28.520
It is made of metal and leather.

01:28.522 --> 01:30.456
A hundred feet of tape
comes from one end.

01:30.458 --> 01:32.557
♪♪

01:32.559 --> 01:34.793
WILDMAN:
This surveyor's measuring tape

01:34.795 --> 01:37.529
was at the center
of an epic expedition

01:37.531 --> 01:39.531
to protect America's homeland.

01:39.533 --> 01:43.602
This is the story of a daunting
task and men who defied nature.

01:43.604 --> 01:47.906
♪♪

01:47.908 --> 01:52.277
WILDMAN: January 1942 --
It's barely a month

01:52.279 --> 01:55.681
after the devastating
Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor,

01:55.683 --> 01:58.316
and the United States
is still reeling.

01:58.318 --> 02:01.419
While the U.S. mainland
is considered to be out of range

02:01.421 --> 02:03.489
from conventional
Japanese weapons,

02:03.491 --> 02:08.193
one territory remains at risk --
Alaska.

02:08.195 --> 02:11.296
Fearing that Alaska could be
the next target

02:11.298 --> 02:14.366
for a Japanese assault,
the American military chiefs

02:14.368 --> 02:16.835
begin a program of supplying
and fortifying

02:16.837 --> 02:19.504
their installations
in the frozen north,

02:19.506 --> 02:21.006
but there's a problem --

02:21.008 --> 02:23.575
the Japanese navy
is patrolling the waters

02:23.577 --> 02:24.910
of the northern Pacific,

02:24.912 --> 02:28.213
preventing U.S. supply ships
from getting through.

02:28.215 --> 02:32.517
And the route by air, beset by
high mountains and icy weather,

02:32.519 --> 02:34.219
is no less treacherous.

02:34.221 --> 02:36.989
WEATHERFORD: Flying was really
challenging for these pilots,

02:36.991 --> 02:38.790
mostly due
to uncharted territory

02:38.792 --> 02:40.592
and threats
from weather conditions.

02:40.594 --> 02:42.594
♪♪

02:42.596 --> 02:44.662
WILDMAN: Determined
to protect the region

02:44.664 --> 02:46.464
from the advancing Japanese,

02:46.466 --> 02:48.666
U.S. president
Franklin D. Roosevelt

02:48.668 --> 02:50.402
makes a fateful decision.

02:50.404 --> 02:52.371
He orders the construction

02:52.373 --> 02:55.207
of a 1,500-mile
emergency supply route

02:55.209 --> 02:58.476
which will link the remote
Alaskan military bases

02:58.478 --> 03:00.379
to the road system in Canada.

03:00.381 --> 03:02.947
Charged with overseeing
the project

03:02.949 --> 03:07.352
is 48-year-old military engineer
Colonel William Hodge.

03:07.354 --> 03:10.822
WEATHERFORD: Colonel William
Hodge was a decorated war hero

03:10.824 --> 03:13.225
and had previously led
an army battalion

03:13.227 --> 03:16.361
creating roads and bridges
in the Philippines.

03:16.363 --> 03:18.397
His superiors knew
that if anybody was able

03:18.399 --> 03:20.766
to get this project completed,
it was him.

03:20.768 --> 03:23.969
WILDMAN: Nevertheless,
it's a daunting task.

03:23.971 --> 03:26.772
Much of the Alaskan territory
was unmapped

03:26.774 --> 03:28.406
and heavily forested.

03:28.408 --> 03:29.675
♪♪

03:29.677 --> 03:31.376
WILDMAN:
Not only that,

03:31.378 --> 03:33.912
but Hodge's crew
must complete the project

03:33.914 --> 03:36.315
before the next Alaskan winter
sets in.

03:36.317 --> 03:37.983
WEATHERFORD:
It would've been difficult

03:37.985 --> 03:39.284
under any circumstances,

03:39.286 --> 03:40.985
but the fact that they were
trying to complete this

03:40.987 --> 03:43.655
in just eight months
was almost crazy.

03:43.657 --> 03:48.827
WILDMAN: On February 14th,
Colonel Hodge and his team

03:48.829 --> 03:51.697
begin surveying
the unfamiliar landscape.

03:51.699 --> 03:54.633
In their tool kit
is the measuring tape

03:54.635 --> 03:56.268
which is now on display

03:56.270 --> 03:59.004
at the University of Alaska
Museum of the North.

03:59.006 --> 04:01.072
WEATHERFORD: He decided
the best place to start

04:01.074 --> 04:03.375
would be near Dawson Creek
in Canada

04:03.377 --> 04:04.977
because the land
was relatively level

04:04.979 --> 04:07.178
and there was
a railway connection.

04:07.180 --> 04:09.548
WILDMAN: With the first
few miles plotted out,

04:09.550 --> 04:11.016
construction begins.

04:11.018 --> 04:12.751
WEATHERFORD:
Thousands of workers

04:12.753 --> 04:14.586
from the
U.S. Army Corps of Engineers

04:14.588 --> 04:16.488
and civilians
arrived in the area,

04:16.490 --> 04:19.157
along with hundreds of pieces
of construction equipment.

04:19.159 --> 04:22.761
WILDMAN: Initially, the men make
slow but steady progress,

04:22.763 --> 04:25.897
averaging a meager
two to four miles per day,

04:25.899 --> 04:28.033
but a few months
into the project,

04:28.035 --> 04:30.068
Hodge and his crew
come face to face

04:30.070 --> 04:32.938
with a seemingly
insurmountable challenge --

04:32.940 --> 04:35.740
the Rockies.

04:35.742 --> 04:37.576
This epic mountain range

04:37.578 --> 04:40.178
stretches from New Mexico
in the south

04:40.180 --> 04:42.914
all the way
to Northern British Columbia.

04:42.916 --> 04:44.916
WEATHERFORD: Trucks would often
get stuck in the mud.

04:44.918 --> 04:46.718
Equipment would be
bent out of shape.

04:46.720 --> 04:49.821
The workers suffered from
all sorts of ailments,

04:49.823 --> 04:53.391
including frostbite.

04:53.393 --> 04:55.460
WILDMAN:
If Hodge can't pick a route

04:55.462 --> 04:58.196
through the maze of high peaks
and glacial valleys,

04:58.198 --> 05:00.398
his men will never
finish the road on time

05:00.400 --> 05:02.501
and the military bases
will be defenseless

05:02.503 --> 05:04.869
in the face of
the marauding Japanese.

05:04.871 --> 05:08.273
WEATHERFORD: A trail like this
had never been blazed before.

05:08.275 --> 05:11.943
Colonel Hodge had no photographs
or aerial views of this terrain.

05:11.945 --> 05:14.846
WILDMAN: Then there's
an even bigger setback.

05:14.848 --> 05:20.285
On June 6, 1942, the Japanese
invade the Aleutian Islands,

05:20.287 --> 05:24.022
a remote archipelago off the
southwestern coast of Alaska.

05:24.024 --> 05:27.426
Now the enemy has a stepping
stone to the mainland.

05:27.428 --> 05:30.896
Hodge's supply road
is needed more than ever,

05:30.898 --> 05:34.332
but he still has
1,200 miles to build.

05:34.334 --> 05:35.834
WEATHERFORD:
The clock was ticking,

05:35.836 --> 05:38.103
and Colonel Hodge
had to find a way through

05:38.105 --> 05:40.772
one of the most
inhospitable places in America.

05:40.774 --> 05:43.441
WILDMAN:
Surrounded by the mighty peaks

05:43.443 --> 05:46.945
of the Canadian Rockies,
it is almost impossible

05:46.947 --> 05:50.915
for the intrepid engineer
to chart a viable course.

05:50.917 --> 05:54.319
So Colonel Hodge decides
to take to the skies.

05:54.321 --> 05:56.221
WEATHERFORD:
He hired a local bush pilot

05:56.223 --> 05:58.023
to fly him over the terrain

05:58.025 --> 05:59.591
so that using
just his naked eye,

05:59.593 --> 06:01.059
he could figure out
what might work.

06:01.061 --> 06:03.394
♪♪

06:03.396 --> 06:06.431
WILDMAN: It's then that
the answer reveals itself.

06:06.433 --> 06:10.302
From his lofty vantage point,
Hodge spots a narrow,

06:10.304 --> 06:13.805
winding path that weaves
through the maze of valleys.

06:13.807 --> 06:17.809
It's an old dogsled route
carved out by early settlers.

06:17.811 --> 06:20.145
Its name -- the McCusker Trail.

06:20.147 --> 06:23.882
This rugged route had been used
by locals for many years

06:23.884 --> 06:27.119
as a trade route
mostly used by sleigh drivers.

06:27.121 --> 06:28.386
♪♪

06:28.388 --> 06:30.621
WILDMAN: When he lands,
Hodge and his crew

06:30.623 --> 06:33.358
reroute the highway
along this old mountain pass.

06:33.360 --> 06:35.861
WEATHERFORD: The engineers began
pushing forward

06:35.863 --> 06:38.897
at an outstanding
14 miles per day

06:38.899 --> 06:41.833
as compared with their earlier
2 to 4 miles per day.

06:41.835 --> 06:44.635
WILDMAN: Under Colonel Hodge's
leadership,

06:44.637 --> 06:49.907
1,500 miles of roadway
are built in just 8 months.

06:49.909 --> 06:54.045
The road officially opened
in November of 1942.

06:54.047 --> 06:55.580
It's nicknamed the ALCAN,

06:55.582 --> 06:57.749
which is short for
Alaska-Canada Highway.

06:57.751 --> 07:00.685
WILDMAN: Supplies
and reinforcements reach bases

07:00.687 --> 07:02.721
throughout
the Alaskan Territory.

07:02.723 --> 07:05.156
That spring,
American naval forces

07:05.158 --> 07:08.226
retake the Aleutian Islands
from the Japanese,

07:08.228 --> 07:10.795
and it's thanks in part
to the work of

07:10.797 --> 07:13.031
Colonel William Hodge
and his men.

07:13.033 --> 07:14.633
WEATHERFORD:
The Alaska Highway is considered

07:14.635 --> 07:17.302
one of the greatest
engineering feats of all time.

07:17.304 --> 07:22.707
WILDMAN: Today, the ALCAN
is still one of the main routes

07:22.709 --> 07:26.278
used to cross
Alaska's wild landscape,

07:26.280 --> 07:28.146
and this surveyor's
measuring tape

07:28.148 --> 07:30.882
used in the historic
construction project

07:30.884 --> 07:32.584
is on display in Fairbanks

07:32.586 --> 07:35.420
at the University of Alaska
Museum of the North.

07:35.422 --> 07:37.622
It recalls the uphill struggle

07:37.624 --> 07:40.225
to cut a passage
through the wilderness.

07:40.227 --> 07:42.227
♪♪

07:42.229 --> 07:45.197
Spanning the breadth
of Northern England

07:45.199 --> 07:48.500
is a 73-mile-long
stone barricade

07:48.502 --> 07:50.702
that's nearly 2,000 years old.

07:50.704 --> 07:52.537
Known as Hadrian's Wall,

07:52.539 --> 07:56.341
it was built by the Romans
to keep out foreign invaders.

07:56.343 --> 07:59.611
Just to the south lies one of
the most beautiful sections

07:59.613 --> 08:02.848
of the country, the picturesque
lake district of Cumbria.

08:02.850 --> 08:05.517
Here among
the stunning landscapes

08:05.519 --> 08:06.952
and historic buildings

08:06.954 --> 08:10.422
is a unique literary attraction,
Hill Top Farm.

08:10.424 --> 08:11.990
♪♪

08:11.992 --> 08:16.093
This 17th-century stone cottage
was once home

08:16.095 --> 08:19.397
to the iconic children's author
Beatrix Potter.

08:19.399 --> 08:21.799
Today, it's preserved
as a museum

08:21.801 --> 08:23.734
celebrating her life and work.

08:23.736 --> 08:27.605
On display is a wheel
once used for spinning wool,

08:27.607 --> 08:31.509
an unusual square piano
that is strung sideways,

08:31.511 --> 08:34.279
and a doll's house
that Potter used as a reference

08:34.281 --> 08:36.214
for the illustrations
in her book

08:36.216 --> 08:39.651
"The Tale of Two Bad Mice."

08:39.653 --> 08:42.654
Among these cherished
personal possessions

08:42.656 --> 08:45.757
is one object
that's instantly recognizable.

08:45.759 --> 08:50.095
The artifact measures 10 1/2
inches tall by 5 inches wide.

08:50.097 --> 08:53.631
It's made of felt,
leather, and velour.

08:53.633 --> 08:57.102
It is brown in color
and has two ears and a tail.

08:57.104 --> 08:58.703
It's well-worn from age,

08:58.705 --> 09:02.173
and it's dressed in
a blue jacket and red slippers.

09:02.175 --> 09:04.108
WILDMAN:
This simple toy

09:04.110 --> 09:06.978
recalls the true tale
behind a literary legacy.

09:06.980 --> 09:12.083
This is a story about a curious
rabbit and a fairy-tale romance.

09:12.085 --> 09:14.185
♪♪

09:14.187 --> 09:18.089
WILDMAN:
It's 1893 in London, England.

09:18.091 --> 09:22.494
27-year-old Beatrix Potter
dreams of being an artist.

09:22.496 --> 09:24.462
HYDE:
Beatrix Potter was unmarried,

09:24.464 --> 09:26.931
which was unusual
at the time for that age,

09:26.933 --> 09:30.068
and she had a passion
for animals, for nature.

09:30.070 --> 09:32.203
And she was
a very gifted artist.

09:32.205 --> 09:34.372
♪♪

09:34.374 --> 09:37.609
WILDMAN: One day, she learns
that the son of a family friend

09:37.611 --> 09:41.379
is sick with a deadly infection
known as scarlet fever.

09:41.381 --> 09:43.949
To cheer up the youth,
she pens a little story

09:43.951 --> 09:47.686
based on one of her beloved pets
and sends it to him.

09:47.688 --> 09:49.888
HYDE: She wrote him
an eight-page letter,

09:49.890 --> 09:54.392
which included illustrations
of her favorite rabbit, Peter.

09:54.394 --> 09:55.894
That was a really kind thing
to do.

09:55.896 --> 09:58.897
WILDMAN: The tale describes
how a mischievous rabbit

09:58.899 --> 10:00.431
disobeys his mother

10:00.433 --> 10:04.936
and goes in search of lettuce
in a nearby garden.

10:04.938 --> 10:09.240
When the letter arrives, it does
wonders for the child's spirits.

10:09.242 --> 10:11.776
HYDE: It was received
absolutely brilliantly.

10:11.778 --> 10:14.045
WILDMAN:
This gives Potter a bold idea.

10:14.047 --> 10:16.648
This positive response
made Potter wonder,

10:16.650 --> 10:19.250
if one boy likes this so much,

10:19.252 --> 10:21.486
perhaps she could
turn these into a book

10:21.488 --> 10:24.122
and share them
with other children, too.

10:24.124 --> 10:26.491
WILDMAN: So the young artist
expands her story

10:26.493 --> 10:28.593
into an illustrated manuscript

10:28.595 --> 10:31.596
and names it
"The Tale of Peter Rabbit."

10:31.598 --> 10:34.366
She sends it to publishers
throughout England

10:34.368 --> 10:36.534
in hopes that one of them
will pick it up.

10:36.536 --> 10:41.072
But much to her dismay,
the response is lukewarm.

10:41.074 --> 10:45.810
The book is too small, they say,
and will never make any money.

10:45.812 --> 10:47.879
HYDE: This must have been
really downheartening

10:47.881 --> 10:49.947
because she knew
she had something good,

10:49.949 --> 10:51.483
but she kept getting rejections.

10:51.485 --> 10:53.718
♪♪

10:53.720 --> 10:55.420
WILDMAN:
So what will it take

10:55.422 --> 10:58.890
for Beatrix Potter
to hop into the history books?

10:58.892 --> 11:01.860
♪♪

11:04.014 --> 11:05.013
♪♪

11:05.015 --> 11:08.149
It's 1901 in London, England.

11:08.151 --> 11:12.053
Beatrix Potter has just written
a charming children's story

11:12.055 --> 11:15.223
inspired by her beloved
pet rabbit Peter,

11:15.225 --> 11:17.692
but no one wants to publish it.

11:17.694 --> 11:20.561
So what will it take
to give this rabbit's tale

11:20.563 --> 11:21.863
a happy ending?

11:21.865 --> 11:24.499
After many months of rejections,

11:24.501 --> 11:27.968
Potter decides to take matters
into her own hands.

11:27.970 --> 11:32.607
She pays to print 250 copies
of "The Tale Of Peter Rabbit,"

11:32.609 --> 11:36.711
complete with 41
black-and-white illustrations,

11:36.713 --> 11:39.113
and sets out
to sell them herself.

11:39.115 --> 11:41.349
Potter had that creative genius.

11:41.351 --> 11:44.552
♪♪

11:44.554 --> 11:46.521
WILDMAN: She starts out
by peddling her prose

11:46.523 --> 11:47.588
to friends and neighbors,

11:47.590 --> 11:51.726
and just as she hoped,
it's a huge hit.

11:51.728 --> 11:54.896
Hearing of her success, a small
family-run publishing house

11:54.898 --> 11:57.398
named Frederick Warne & Co.

11:57.400 --> 12:01.903
that has previously rejected
Potter takes a second look.

12:01.905 --> 12:05.607
HYDE: In 1901,
Beatrix Potter finally had

12:05.609 --> 12:07.942
the positive response
that she needed.

12:07.944 --> 12:09.110
Frederick Warne & Co.

12:09.112 --> 12:12.013
wanted to publish
Beatrix Potter's book.

12:12.015 --> 12:15.349
Beatrix Potter
must've been really excited.

12:15.351 --> 12:17.819
It's a long, hard slog
to get something published,

12:17.821 --> 12:19.420
and she'd finally found someone

12:19.422 --> 12:21.756
who could see the same thing
that she could in her work.

12:21.758 --> 12:24.392
WILDMAN:
She creates color illustrations,

12:24.394 --> 12:27.228
and the following year,
"The Tale of Peter Rabbit"

12:27.230 --> 12:29.931
is officially released
to a rapturous reception.

12:29.933 --> 12:33.368
Children are enamored with the
adventures of the brazen bunny.

12:33.370 --> 12:36.104
HYDE: Potter had success
beyond her wildest dreams.

12:36.106 --> 12:38.973
The publishing company
had to produce six editions

12:38.975 --> 12:40.375
just to keep up with demand.

12:40.377 --> 12:44.479
Potter had gone from complete
obscurity through rejection

12:44.481 --> 12:46.448
to being a best-selling author.

12:46.450 --> 12:48.082
Potter must've been
over the moon.

12:48.084 --> 12:51.986
♪♪

12:51.988 --> 12:55.055
WILDMAN: But Potter gets more
out of her publishing deal

12:55.057 --> 12:56.691
than she could've imagined.

12:56.693 --> 12:59.260
She falls in love
with her editor,

12:59.262 --> 13:01.262
33-year-old Norman Warne,

13:01.264 --> 13:03.531
and he asks
for her hand in marriage.

13:03.533 --> 13:05.767
HYDE:
Potter was on top of the world.

13:05.769 --> 13:08.336
She gave him
an illustration of Cinderella

13:08.338 --> 13:10.404
going to the ball in a pumpkin

13:10.406 --> 13:13.908
pulled not by horses
but by rabbits.

13:13.910 --> 13:16.744
WILDMAN: Using the royalties
from her book,

13:16.746 --> 13:20.014
she purchases a country home
in Cumbria, England,

13:20.016 --> 13:22.016
called Hill Top Farm.

13:22.018 --> 13:25.220
To Potter,
it's the perfect place to write.

13:25.222 --> 13:28.523
Hill Top Farm became
a sanctuary for Potter.

13:28.525 --> 13:31.860
She had a passion
for animals, for nature.

13:31.862 --> 13:34.896
It was beautiful,
serene, nurturing.

13:34.898 --> 13:37.832
She was very much at home there.

13:37.834 --> 13:40.635
WILDMAN:
Inspired by her surroundings,

13:40.637 --> 13:44.105
Potter creates more than two
dozen charming children's books

13:44.107 --> 13:45.472
in her lifetime,

13:45.474 --> 13:48.776
and Potter's classic story,
"The Tale of Peter Rabbit,"

13:48.778 --> 13:52.313
has sold more than
45 million copies to date.

13:52.315 --> 13:55.316
HYDE: Potter's love
inspired her creativity,

13:55.318 --> 13:56.851
and that's gone on
to produce work

13:56.853 --> 13:59.320
that has made
generations of children happy.

13:59.322 --> 14:01.489
♪♪

14:01.491 --> 14:04.959
WILDMAN: Today, this
110-year-old Peter Rabbit toy

14:04.961 --> 14:08.997
remains on display at the Hill
Top Farm in Cumbria, England.

14:08.999 --> 14:13.200
It recalls the unlikely tale of
a beloved children's character

14:13.202 --> 14:16.004
that hopped
well beyond expectations.

14:16.006 --> 14:18.072
♪♪

14:18.074 --> 14:22.276
For a mere four months in 1783,

14:22.278 --> 14:24.011
the city of Princeton,
New Jersey,

14:24.013 --> 14:26.781
was the capital
of the United States,

14:26.783 --> 14:29.150
and on the campus
of Princeton University

14:29.152 --> 14:32.287
is a building that served
as the then seat of government,

14:32.289 --> 14:33.988
Nassau Hall.

14:33.990 --> 14:37.224
It was here that Congress
congratulated George Washington

14:37.226 --> 14:39.794
on winning
the Revolutionary War.

14:39.796 --> 14:42.764
And just steps
from this iconic edifice

14:42.766 --> 14:45.733
is another of the nation's
oldest institutions,

14:45.735 --> 14:48.603
the Princeton University
Art Museum.

14:48.605 --> 14:50.904
♪♪

14:50.906 --> 14:54.709
Among the collection
is an 1884 oil painting

14:54.711 --> 14:57.645
by the French artist
Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec

14:57.647 --> 14:59.947
titled "The Sacred Grove,"

14:59.949 --> 15:04.085
Paul Cezanne's "Cistern in
the Park of Chateau Noir,"

15:04.087 --> 15:07.255
and Claude Monet's
1899 masterpiece

15:07.257 --> 15:09.591
"Water Lilies
and Japanese Bridge."

15:09.593 --> 15:11.926
♪♪

15:11.928 --> 15:14.362
But among
these colorful canvases

15:14.364 --> 15:16.598
is an object carved in stone.

15:16.600 --> 15:21.436
The artifact is about 28 inches
high and 22 inches wide.

15:21.438 --> 15:24.872
Symbols have been expertly
carved into its surface.

15:24.874 --> 15:28.610
It's thousands of years old,
and it weighs nearly half a ton.

15:28.612 --> 15:32.213
WILDMAN: This ancient
Egyptian relic recalls

15:32.215 --> 15:35.149
an extraordinary tale
of discovery and loss

15:35.151 --> 15:38.086
that played out
on the raging seas.

15:38.088 --> 15:41.322
BRIER: This is the story of
one captain's determination

15:41.324 --> 15:43.691
to save something
once thought lost.

15:43.693 --> 15:48.162
♪♪

15:50.566 --> 15:53.300
WILDMAN:
It's October 1877.

15:53.302 --> 15:56.671
A merchant ship named
the SS<i> Fitzmaurice</i>

15:56.673 --> 15:58.840
is en route from Scotland
to Spain

15:58.842 --> 16:01.009
carrying a cargo of iron.

16:01.011 --> 16:05.079
Midway through the voyage,
it encounters a brutal storm,

16:05.081 --> 16:09.150
but it's nothing Captain
James Evans can't handle.

16:09.152 --> 16:12.086
BRIER: James Evans was
an experienced sea captain.

16:12.088 --> 16:13.888
Evans had been through storms
before.

16:13.890 --> 16:15.890
He had sailed
in these waters repeatedly.

16:15.892 --> 16:17.458
He wasn't afraid.

16:17.460 --> 16:19.594
He knew what to do,
and he was going to do it.

16:19.596 --> 16:21.829
♪♪

16:21.831 --> 16:23.998
WILDMAN:
When the skies finally clear,

16:24.000 --> 16:27.268
Evans spots a mysterious shape
looming on the horizon.

16:27.270 --> 16:30.538
He came upon something
that he wasn't sure what it was.

16:30.540 --> 16:33.808
He got out his binoculars,
and Evan saw something

16:33.810 --> 16:36.744
the likes of which
he had never seen at sea.

16:36.746 --> 16:38.980
It was on its side,
and it wasn't moving.

16:38.982 --> 16:42.417
WILDMAN: Intrigued,
Evans steers the<i> Fitzmaurice</i>

16:42.419 --> 16:45.153
towards the strange
floating object,

16:45.155 --> 16:48.990
and as he gets closer, a bizarre
sight comes into view --

16:48.992 --> 16:55.629
a gigantic metallic cylinder
almost 100 feet long.

16:55.631 --> 16:59.900
Whatever it is, this weird
vessel appears to be abandoned.

16:59.902 --> 17:03.104
He hailed it, calling,
"Is anybody there?"

17:03.106 --> 17:04.972
But there was no answer.

17:04.974 --> 17:06.841
He couldn't see
any signs of life.

17:06.843 --> 17:09.944
WILDMAN: The baffled sea captain
then makes a fateful decision.

17:09.946 --> 17:13.314
Maritime law dictates
that any unmanned craft

17:13.316 --> 17:16.184
can be claimed
by the person who finds it,

17:16.186 --> 17:19.921
so Evans concludes
the ship is now his.

17:19.923 --> 17:24.058
According to the laws
of the sea, he owns it.

17:24.060 --> 17:27.194
WILDMAN: But the question
remains, what is it?

17:27.196 --> 17:30.998
The captain and his men take
a rowboat to the wayward vessel.

17:31.000 --> 17:34.936
Evans and his crew must have
been wondering, "What's inside?"

17:34.938 --> 17:37.338
WILDMAN:
But because of the rough waters,

17:37.340 --> 17:41.075
they're unable to get onboard,
so they hook a line to it

17:41.077 --> 17:43.811
and decide to tow
the mysterious craft to port.

17:43.813 --> 17:45.346
BRIER:
It was dangerous.

17:45.348 --> 17:47.315
The vessel was bobbing
up and down,

17:47.317 --> 17:50.351
but he was determined
to get his catch in.

17:50.353 --> 17:52.286
WILDMAN:
Little does Evans realize

17:52.288 --> 17:54.822
he's towing something
far more valuable

17:54.824 --> 17:56.357
than he ever could've imagined.

17:56.359 --> 17:58.493
♪♪

17:58.495 --> 18:01.829
Eventually, the sailors
reach port in Spain,

18:01.831 --> 18:04.498
and Evans is finally able
to uncover

18:04.500 --> 18:06.500
the true nature of his haul.

18:06.502 --> 18:09.070
BRIER: I think Evans
must've been excited.

18:09.072 --> 18:11.839
He probably had a candle
or a lantern with him

18:11.841 --> 18:15.510
so he could see,
and he saw a hatch in the floor.

18:15.512 --> 18:17.511
And he went inside the hatch.

18:17.513 --> 18:20.915
WILDMAN: Evans slowly
lowers himself into the chamber.

18:20.917 --> 18:23.851
There before him,
shimmering in the half light,

18:23.853 --> 18:28.923
is a huge slab of polished stone
almost 70 feet long.

18:28.925 --> 18:32.727
BRIER: It was unlike anything
Evans had ever seen.

18:32.729 --> 18:34.394
It was incredible.

18:34.396 --> 18:37.865
WILDMAN: So what is the secret
of this strange object?

18:37.867 --> 18:40.134
♪♪

18:42.005 --> 18:43.537
♪♪

18:43.539 --> 18:45.807
It's 1877.

18:45.809 --> 18:48.542
Sea captain James Evans
has just come upon

18:48.544 --> 18:52.013
an extraordinary object floating
in the middle of the ocean --

18:52.015 --> 18:55.616
a gigantic iron cylinder
sealed at both ends.

18:55.618 --> 18:57.652
Thinking the mysterious tube

18:57.654 --> 18:59.153
might contain
something valuable,

18:59.155 --> 19:01.789
Evans tows it
to the nearest port.

19:01.791 --> 19:03.791
But when he finally
takes a peek inside,

19:03.793 --> 19:07.461
the intrepid mariner
gets the shock of his life.

19:07.463 --> 19:10.064
So what's the story
behind this bizarre vessel

19:10.066 --> 19:12.200
and its incredible cargo?

19:12.202 --> 19:16.938
The story begins more than
half a century earlier in Egypt.

19:16.940 --> 19:19.207
As a token of gratitude
for defending Egypt

19:19.209 --> 19:20.641
against the French,

19:20.643 --> 19:24.311
the Egyptian government gave
the British government a gift.

19:24.313 --> 19:28.249
BRIER: It was an obelisk,
an ancient Egyptian monument

19:28.251 --> 19:32.453
that had stood at Alexandria
Harbor for 2,000 years.

19:32.455 --> 19:36.290
It was originally erected
by the Pharaoh Thutmosis III

19:36.292 --> 19:39.727
in a place called Heliopolis
near Cairo,

19:39.729 --> 19:43.931
but then, in Roman times,
was erected at Alexandria.

19:43.933 --> 19:46.067
♪♪

19:46.069 --> 19:49.537
WILDMAN: To bring the enormous
relic back to Britain,

19:49.539 --> 19:52.606
the British built
a one-of-a-kind metal ship

19:52.608 --> 19:54.275
to transport the monolith.

19:54.277 --> 19:55.943
It held six sailors

19:55.945 --> 19:58.813
and was going to be towed
by a powerful steamer.

19:58.815 --> 20:01.615
BRIER: The iron vessel
had been specially designed

20:01.617 --> 20:04.685
to house the obelisk
and bring it back to England.

20:04.687 --> 20:08.289
WILDMAN: On September 21st,
the ships set sail for England,

20:08.291 --> 20:12.026
but three weeks into the voyage,
they hit a terrible storm

20:12.028 --> 20:13.694
and the tow rope is severed.

20:13.696 --> 20:15.429
BRIER:
They hit a gale.

20:15.431 --> 20:18.299
The captain knew --
keep it into the wind.

20:18.301 --> 20:21.502
You had to head into the wind,
but the gale got even worse.

20:21.504 --> 20:24.571
And eventually,
a huge wave came up,

20:24.573 --> 20:27.575
crashed down
on the brave sailors,

20:27.577 --> 20:29.977
and they were never seen again.

20:29.979 --> 20:30.912
♪♪

20:30.914 --> 20:33.247
WILDMAN:
With the tow rope split

20:33.249 --> 20:35.583
and the cylinder
nowhere to be seen,

20:35.585 --> 20:39.253
the steamer heads to port
to deliver news of the disaster.

20:39.255 --> 20:42.056
Everyone thought
the obelisk was lost.

20:42.058 --> 20:44.525
WILDMAN: It's then
that Captain James Evans

20:44.527 --> 20:46.994
and the crew
of the SS<i> Fitzmaurice</i>

20:46.996 --> 20:48.996
made their strange discovery,

20:48.998 --> 20:50.798
and the precious monument
was saved.

20:50.800 --> 20:54.601
There was tremendous relief
among the British people

20:54.603 --> 20:57.772
that their obelisk
hadn't been lost.

20:57.774 --> 21:01.141
WILDMAN: A few months later,
the relic reaches London

21:01.143 --> 21:03.677
and is erected along
the River Thames.

21:03.679 --> 21:06.213
It's given the name
Cleopatra's Needle.

21:06.215 --> 21:10.017
It's so popular that similar
structures are also put up

21:10.019 --> 21:11.752
in New York's Central Park

21:11.754 --> 21:14.154
and in Paris
near the Seine River.

21:14.156 --> 21:17.691
And as for Evans,
British authorities reward him

21:17.693 --> 21:24.231
with a staggering sum of £2,000,
worth nearly $300,000 today.

21:24.233 --> 21:26.233
BRIER: Evans knew that
he was part of history.

21:26.235 --> 21:28.703
He had done something
no one else had ever done --

21:28.705 --> 21:32.173
found an obelisk at sea
and brought it safely to shore.

21:32.175 --> 21:34.208
♪♪

21:34.210 --> 21:37.178
WILDMAN: Today, this fragment
of an ancient obelisk

21:37.180 --> 21:40.113
made from the same granite
as the one Evans recovered

21:40.115 --> 21:41.349
sits on display

21:41.351 --> 21:44.819
at the Princeton University
Art Museum in New Jersey.

21:44.821 --> 21:47.687
It recalls the story
of an intrepid captain

21:47.689 --> 21:49.357
and his monumental struggle

21:49.359 --> 21:52.259
to save one of the world's
great treasures.

21:52.261 --> 21:54.662
♪♪

21:54.664 --> 21:58.299
Milwaukee, Wisconsin, is known
as the beer capital of the world

21:58.301 --> 22:01.602
thanks to its German heritage
and abundance of wheat.

22:01.604 --> 22:04.738
Today, it's home to
more than 40 breweries,

22:04.740 --> 22:07.742
but one local institution
celebrates culture

22:07.744 --> 22:09.477
from much further afield.

22:09.479 --> 22:12.546
This is
the Milwaukee Public Museum.

22:12.548 --> 22:13.814
♪♪

22:13.816 --> 22:16.950
On display is a collection
of Egyptian stone jars

22:16.952 --> 22:21.522
that once held human organs
and date back to 800 BCE,

22:21.524 --> 22:25.425
a piece of ivory carved in China
during the Qing dynasty,

22:25.427 --> 22:27.161
and a ceremonial costume

22:27.163 --> 22:31.799
that portrays a demon
from the island of Bali.

22:31.801 --> 22:34.434
But there is
one simple-looking item

22:34.436 --> 22:36.070
that hails from closer to home.

22:36.072 --> 22:40.441
WINTERS: The artifact is 32
inches long and 6 inches wide.

22:40.443 --> 22:42.843
It is carved
from polished hickory wood,

22:42.845 --> 22:43.911
and one end of it

22:43.913 --> 22:46.313
has been expertly bent
into a perfect ring.

22:46.315 --> 22:48.248
♪♪

22:48.250 --> 22:51.185
WILDMAN: This elegant
Native American instrument

22:51.187 --> 22:54.755
harkens back to one of history's
most cunning ruses.

22:54.757 --> 22:58.025
WINTERS: This object represents
one man's unexpected strategy

22:58.027 --> 22:59.660
to protect his people.

22:59.662 --> 23:02.062
[ Indistinct shouting ]

23:02.064 --> 23:04.331
♪♪

23:04.333 --> 23:07.134
WILDMAN:
It's 1763.

23:07.136 --> 23:10.204
British settlers are moving west
across North America,

23:10.206 --> 23:13.641
driving out native tribes
who stand in their way.

23:13.643 --> 23:18.145
In Michigan, one particular
tribe known as the Ojibwe

23:18.147 --> 23:21.081
is feeling the brunt
of the settlers' cruel regime,

23:21.083 --> 23:24.585
but they are not about to yield
to the British without a fight.

23:24.587 --> 23:29.023
Leading the charge is
a bold warrior named Minweweh.

23:29.025 --> 23:31.558
WINTERS:
Minweweh was passionate.

23:31.560 --> 23:35.096
He was committed
to his people's rights,

23:35.098 --> 23:37.698
and he was virulently
anti-British.

23:37.700 --> 23:38.899
♪♪

23:38.901 --> 23:42.069
WILDMAN: Minweweh wants
to drive the British

23:42.071 --> 23:45.239
out of the Ojibwe territory
by recapturing

23:45.241 --> 23:48.309
a British stronghold
named Fort Michilimackinac.

23:48.311 --> 23:51.479
WINTERS: The fort in question
was filled with British

23:51.481 --> 23:53.447
who had arrived
a few years earlier.

23:53.449 --> 23:54.915
♪♪

23:54.917 --> 23:58.385
WILDMAN: But taking the fort
will be no easy feat.

23:58.387 --> 24:01.255
WINTERS:
The walls are just unclimbable.

24:01.257 --> 24:04.658
You would have soldiers
on top of the palisaded walls,

24:04.660 --> 24:06.927
of course, armed with guns.

24:06.929 --> 24:10.331
A frontal assault
on Fort Michilimackinac

24:10.333 --> 24:14.568
was not a wise course of action.

24:14.570 --> 24:17.104
WILDMAN:
Minweweh wants to use cunning

24:17.106 --> 24:19.240
rather than brute force.

24:19.242 --> 24:21.542
WINTERS: He had to come up
with a strategy

24:21.544 --> 24:24.411
that would not give
the impression of an attack.

24:24.413 --> 24:27.013
WILDMAN:
Rather than fight them head-on,

24:27.015 --> 24:29.116
Minweweh
will ambush the British,

24:29.118 --> 24:30.951
and at the heart of his plan

24:30.953 --> 24:34.088
is a popular Native American
game named baaga'adowe.

24:34.090 --> 24:35.956
♪♪

24:35.958 --> 24:40.294
The game involves two teams
squaring off against each other

24:40.296 --> 24:42.263
from opposing sides of a field.

24:42.265 --> 24:45.132
Players must catch,
carry, or throw a ball

24:45.134 --> 24:47.501
down the field to score a goal.

24:47.503 --> 24:49.637
Each player uses a wooden stick,

24:49.639 --> 24:53.774
just like the one on display
at the Milwaukee Public Museum.

24:53.776 --> 24:55.643
The British, it seems,

24:55.645 --> 24:57.978
are particularly drawn
to the sport.

24:57.980 --> 25:01.148
WINTERS: There was
this tradition of playing games

25:01.150 --> 25:02.583
out in front of the fort.

25:02.585 --> 25:06.320
British troops
very much enjoyed watching.

25:06.322 --> 25:08.689
WILDMAN:
So on June 2nd,

25:08.691 --> 25:11.926
Minweweh
and more than 400 natives

25:11.928 --> 25:13.460
approached the fort
under the pretense

25:13.462 --> 25:15.462
of playing a game
of baaga'adowe.

25:15.464 --> 25:18.365
WINTERS: I would imagine
that Minweweh at this point

25:18.367 --> 25:20.201
was quite nervous.

25:20.203 --> 25:22.869
This was an untested method.

25:22.871 --> 25:25.272
WILDMAN: The British troops
gather 'round,

25:25.274 --> 25:26.874
and at the appointed hour,

25:26.876 --> 25:29.576
one of Minweweh's warriors
lifts his stick

25:29.578 --> 25:31.445
and the game begins.

25:31.447 --> 25:32.913
WINTERS:
The ball was in play

25:32.915 --> 25:35.583
for Minweweh's plan
to capture the British fort.

25:35.585 --> 25:40.020
WILDMAN: So will this
sporting ruse actually work?

25:40.022 --> 25:44.325
♪♪

25:46.011 --> 25:47.478
♪♪

25:47.480 --> 25:50.247
It's 1763 in Michigan.

25:50.249 --> 25:53.951
At a British stronghold
named Fort Michilimackinac,

25:53.953 --> 25:56.253
a strange series of events
is unfolding.

25:56.255 --> 26:00.291
An astute warrior named Minweweh
has invited the British

26:00.293 --> 26:03.827
to watch a traditional Native
game known as baaga'adowe.

26:03.829 --> 26:06.697
But there's more to
this tribal sporting match

26:06.699 --> 26:08.032
than meets the eye.

26:08.034 --> 26:09.199
♪♪

26:09.201 --> 26:11.535
As the ball is lofted
into the air,

26:11.537 --> 26:14.304
the British soldiers
at the fort are captivated.

26:14.306 --> 26:17.841
Minweweh, I'm sure,
saw this opening and realized

26:17.843 --> 26:21.045
that this was the moment
to put his plan into action.

26:21.047 --> 26:22.346
♪♪

26:22.348 --> 26:25.181
WILDMAN: Seeing their chance,
Minweweh signals

26:25.183 --> 26:29.053
a group of Ojibwe women to walk
toward the entrance of the fort.

26:29.055 --> 26:32.188
Once they are in place,
a player tosses the ball

26:32.190 --> 26:35.125
straight at the open gate,
and chaos erupts.

26:35.127 --> 26:38.762
Some signal was passed between
the players on the field.

26:38.764 --> 26:42.199
En masse, almost 500 people
charged the gates.

26:42.201 --> 26:44.335
♪♪

26:44.337 --> 26:47.471
WILDMAN:
The British stand by dumbfounded

26:47.473 --> 26:50.140
as the tribesmen
race towards the fort.

26:50.142 --> 26:53.143
At the gate, the Ojibwe women
throw open their cloaks.

26:53.145 --> 26:58.415
Underneath, they have hidden
dozens of tomahawks and spears.

26:58.417 --> 27:00.283
The women at the gates
were handing out weapons

27:00.285 --> 27:01.685
as they were charging through.

27:01.687 --> 27:03.553
WILDMAN:
Cut off from their arsenal,

27:03.555 --> 27:05.622
the British troops
are easily defeated.

27:05.624 --> 27:07.524
♪♪

27:07.526 --> 27:11.996
WINTERS: During the attack,
Minweweh lost very few people.

27:11.998 --> 27:17.067
He must have felt elated
that his plan had succeeded

27:17.069 --> 27:21.739
and that he had dealt a pretty
serious blow to the British.

27:21.741 --> 27:23.974
WILDMAN:
The Ojibwe take the fort

27:23.976 --> 27:25.976
and distribute
all of the supplies

27:25.978 --> 27:27.144
and goods they find.

27:27.146 --> 27:30.247
In response to the attack
and others, as well,

27:30.249 --> 27:31.715
in October of that year,

27:31.717 --> 27:34.852
the British reform their
policies regarding the natives.

27:34.854 --> 27:38.555
The British response to this was
the realization that they needed

27:38.557 --> 27:42.726
to be more amenable
to their Indian neighbors.

27:42.728 --> 27:44.762
♪♪

27:44.764 --> 27:48.265
WILDMAN: The sport that fooled
the settlers, baaga'adowe,

27:48.267 --> 27:51.635
grows more and more popular
in the centuries that follow.

27:51.637 --> 27:53.670
Today, it's known as lacrosse.

27:53.672 --> 27:56.139
WINTERS:
High schools and universities

27:56.141 --> 27:57.441
have national teams.

27:57.443 --> 28:00.744
There are even
some international competitions,

28:00.746 --> 28:02.746
and tribes like the Ojibwe

28:02.748 --> 28:06.616
still carry on
this tradition of lacrosse.

28:06.618 --> 28:09.619
WILDMAN: And this
Native American lacrosse stick

28:09.621 --> 28:11.422
sits on display
within the collection

28:11.424 --> 28:14.157
of the Milwaukee Public Museum
in Wisconsin.

28:14.159 --> 28:15.826
It's a reminder that sometimes,

28:15.828 --> 28:18.695
dropping the ball
can be a winning strategy.

28:18.697 --> 28:21.198
♪♪

28:21.200 --> 28:25.436
Near Pensacola, Florida,
is the longest stretch

28:25.438 --> 28:28.305
of protected shoreline
in the United States,

28:28.307 --> 28:30.841
the Gulf Islands
National Seashore,

28:30.843 --> 28:34.044
and this magnificent coastline
is home to a host

28:34.046 --> 28:37.948
of wonderful creatures,
including great blue herons,

28:37.950 --> 28:41.785
bottlenose dolphins,
and sea turtles.

28:41.787 --> 28:45.722
But not far from this
natural refuge is an institution

28:45.724 --> 28:48.158
that trumpets
man-made marvels --

28:48.160 --> 28:50.928
the National
Naval Aviation Museum.

28:50.930 --> 28:52.296
♪♪

28:52.298 --> 28:55.399
Among the artifacts on display

28:55.401 --> 28:58.135
is a gondola
from an Allied airship

28:58.137 --> 29:01.905
used to scout for German U-boats
during World War II,

29:01.907 --> 29:06.076
a fighter aircraft that survived
the attack on Pearl Harbor,

29:06.078 --> 29:08.145
and a Cadet biplane flown

29:08.147 --> 29:12.549
by President George H.W. Bush
in 1943.

29:12.551 --> 29:15.886
But one item
in this military collection

29:15.888 --> 29:18.422
is linked to
a peacetime operation

29:18.424 --> 29:19.756
that went horribly wrong.

29:19.758 --> 29:21.425
GOODSPEED:
It's made of metal.

29:21.427 --> 29:24.661
It is grey and white
with touches of silver.

29:24.663 --> 29:26.530
It has three wheels.

29:26.532 --> 29:31.568
It is 40 feet long, and it is 44
feet wide at its widest point.

29:31.570 --> 29:34.771
And it can go
over 500 miles per hour.

29:34.773 --> 29:37.774
♪♪

29:37.776 --> 29:40.511
WILDMAN: This fighter jet,
known as a Banshee,

29:40.513 --> 29:42.279
recalls the harrowing mission

29:42.281 --> 29:44.848
that pushed a bold airman
to the limit.

29:44.850 --> 29:47.383
GOODSPEED: This object
represents a young pilot

29:47.385 --> 29:49.586
and a flight
that nearly cost him his life.

29:49.588 --> 29:53.357
♪♪

29:53.359 --> 29:56.927
WILDMAN:
It's February 1954.

29:56.929 --> 30:00.330
Stationed off the Pacific coast
of Japan is a massive,

30:00.332 --> 30:06.703
27,500-ton aircraft carrier,
the U.S.S.<i> Shangri-La.</i>

30:06.705 --> 30:10.006
Onboard the mammoth ship
are nearly 100 planes

30:10.008 --> 30:13.410
and more than 3,000 personnel.

30:13.412 --> 30:17.848
Among them is a 26-year-old
Navy pilot named Jim Lovell.

30:17.850 --> 30:20.617
GOODSPEED: Jim Lovell was
fresh out of flight training

30:20.619 --> 30:23.220
and was certainly living
his dream as a Naval aviator.

30:23.222 --> 30:25.355
He was intelligent,
goal-oriented,

30:25.357 --> 30:27.924
and set high standards
for himself.

30:27.926 --> 30:30.827
WILDMAN:
But Lovell is about to be taken

30:30.829 --> 30:32.696
to the very edge of survival.

30:32.698 --> 30:36.366
One day, the young pilot is sent
on a dangerous training mission

30:36.368 --> 30:38.768
to prepare his squadron
for a possible aerial attack

30:38.770 --> 30:40.303
on the<i> Shangri-La.</i>

30:40.305 --> 30:43.674
Lovell and the two other pilots
will take off from the carrier,

30:43.676 --> 30:46.843
all flying Banshee Jets
just like this one

30:46.845 --> 30:49.746
now on display at the
National Naval Aviation Museum,

30:49.748 --> 30:52.449
but there's a catch.

30:52.451 --> 30:56.720
Lovell and his fellow pilots
will be flying at night.

30:56.722 --> 30:58.855
To simulate wartime operations,

30:58.857 --> 31:01.992
the<i> Shangri-La</i>
will turn off all its lights

31:01.994 --> 31:04.728
and they will cut
all radio contact

31:04.730 --> 31:06.797
between the ship
and the planes.

31:06.799 --> 31:10.333
This was considered one of
the most dangerous things to do

31:10.335 --> 31:12.769
in military aviation.

31:12.771 --> 31:16.006
WILDMAN:
With final preparations made,

31:16.008 --> 31:18.141
Lovell and his colleagues
take off from the deck

31:18.143 --> 31:21.211
of the carrier
and into the dark of night.

31:21.213 --> 31:23.313
Then, the threesome splits up.

31:23.315 --> 31:25.916
GOODSPEED: Lovell
and his squadronmates practiced

31:25.918 --> 31:29.086
what they would do in the event
of an actual combat operation,

31:29.088 --> 31:31.321
which was to intercept
any enemy aircraft

31:31.323 --> 31:33.756
that would be coming out
to attack the carrier.

31:33.758 --> 31:35.425
WILDMAN:
Lovell makes it as far

31:35.427 --> 31:37.261
as the designated
turnaround point,

31:37.263 --> 31:40.497
but on the way back,
disaster strikes.

31:40.499 --> 31:43.700
His navigational panel
short-circuits.

31:43.702 --> 31:47.037
GOODSPEED: They were
the lifeblood of operations.

31:47.039 --> 31:50.440
Without those instruments,
he was in very serious trouble.

31:50.442 --> 31:53.443
WILDMAN: With his systems down
in the darkness,

31:53.445 --> 31:56.179
Lovell quickly loses track
of his position.

31:56.181 --> 31:59.216
He considers radioing back
to base for help,

31:59.218 --> 32:01.918
but if he does,
he fails the exercise.

32:01.920 --> 32:03.953
Under operational conditions,

32:03.955 --> 32:05.588
they would've maintained
radio silence,

32:05.590 --> 32:08.525
so he wanted to use that
as a last resort.

32:08.527 --> 32:12.462
WILDMAN: With no radio or radar,
the odds of finding the vessel

32:12.464 --> 32:15.132
before running out of fuel
are slim at best.

32:15.134 --> 32:17.133
GOODSPEED:
If Lovell had run out of gas,

32:17.135 --> 32:18.669
he would've had to eject
from the aircraft.

32:18.671 --> 32:20.804
He would be landing
in the Pacific Ocean

32:20.806 --> 32:22.139
in the middle of the night.

32:22.141 --> 32:23.573
This routine night flight

32:23.575 --> 32:26.610
had quickly become
Lovell's worst nightmare.

32:26.612 --> 32:29.913
WILDMAN: So how will Lovell
avert catastrophe?

32:29.915 --> 32:32.115
♪♪

32:34.019 --> 32:35.485
♪♪

32:35.487 --> 32:40.290
It's February 1954 in the skies
over the Pacific Ocean.

32:40.292 --> 32:43.093
U.S. fighter pilot Jim Lovell
is in trouble.

32:43.095 --> 32:47.230
A nighttime combat training
mission has gone horribly wrong,

32:47.232 --> 32:50.700
and Lovell has lost contact
with his aircraft carrier.

32:50.702 --> 32:54.237
So how will this American airman
make it back alive?

32:54.239 --> 32:56.973
Lovell faces a grim dilemma --

32:56.975 --> 33:00.777
If he radios for help,
he'll fail the mission.

33:00.779 --> 33:03.714
If he doesn't, his plane
will run out of fuel,

33:03.716 --> 33:06.983
and Lovell will have to eject
and ditch into the ocean.

33:06.985 --> 33:09.486
But just as he is starting
to lose hope,

33:09.488 --> 33:11.455
something bizarre happens.

33:11.457 --> 33:15.992
He sees a greenish glow spread
over the surface of the water.

33:15.994 --> 33:20.197
GOODSPEED: Initially, the glow
on the ocean was very faint,

33:20.199 --> 33:23.800
but as he observed it more
and got closer to it,

33:23.802 --> 33:27.104
the glow became
more and more prominent.

33:27.106 --> 33:29.672
WILDMAN:
What Lovell has stumbled across

33:29.674 --> 33:32.476
is one of nature's
strangest phenomena --

33:32.478 --> 33:35.045
living organisms
that produce light.

33:35.047 --> 33:37.914
It's known as bioluminescence.

33:37.916 --> 33:40.250
Lovell recognizes it
immediately.

33:40.252 --> 33:42.619
When a ship
churns through the ocean,

33:42.621 --> 33:45.188
the spinning propellers
can rouse algae

33:45.190 --> 33:47.591
and cause the organisms
to light up.

33:47.593 --> 33:49.259
If he follows the green path,

33:49.261 --> 33:52.028
it might lead him right back
to the<i> Shangri-La.</i>

33:52.030 --> 33:55.432
GOODSPEED: Lovell knew that this
was not the most reliable way

33:55.434 --> 33:58.001
to find his way back
to the aircraft carrier,

33:58.003 --> 34:01.704
but in his situation, it was
about all that he had left.

34:01.706 --> 34:03.173
♪♪

34:03.175 --> 34:05.742
WILDMAN:
So he follows the trail.

34:05.744 --> 34:09.312
Finally, with his fuel
running dangerously low,

34:09.314 --> 34:11.981
Lovell discerns
the faint outline of a ship

34:11.983 --> 34:12.983
on the horizon.

34:12.985 --> 34:15.385
It's the<i> Shangri-La.</i>

34:15.387 --> 34:18.188
The intrepid pilot
lands on the flight deck

34:18.190 --> 34:20.791
and successfully
completes the mission.

34:20.793 --> 34:23.260
GOODSPEED:
On that particular flight,

34:23.262 --> 34:26.663
Lovell really relied upon
all elements of his training

34:26.665 --> 34:29.933
and just who he was as
an individual and as an aviator.

34:29.935 --> 34:34.337
He met every challenge
that came his way.

34:34.339 --> 34:37.808
WILDMAN: Undaunted by his
death-defying experience,

34:37.810 --> 34:41.144
Lovell continues to hone
his aeronautical skills.

34:41.146 --> 34:44.414
He was chosen for
very challenging assignments,

34:44.416 --> 34:46.549
and with each successive flight,

34:46.551 --> 34:49.386
he gained more confidence
and more skill.

34:49.388 --> 34:53.089
WILDMAN: He even goes on to
become a world-famous astronaut

34:53.091 --> 34:56.993
as the spacecraft commander
of the Apollo 13 mission.

34:56.995 --> 34:59.696
GOODSPEED: All of those flights
that he made later on

34:59.698 --> 35:00.697
in the space program,

35:00.699 --> 35:03.400
flights for which
he achieved great acclaim

35:03.402 --> 35:04.968
and which he demonstrated

35:04.970 --> 35:07.537
just tremendous calm
and cool under pressure,

35:07.539 --> 35:12.075
all of that had been honed
on that dark night.

35:12.077 --> 35:14.110
♪♪

35:14.112 --> 35:16.713
WILDMAN:
Today, this Banshee fighter jet,

35:16.715 --> 35:19.916
the same kind that Lovell flew
on that fateful night,

35:19.918 --> 35:21.318
stands in the collection

35:21.320 --> 35:23.753
at the
National Naval Aviation Museum

35:23.755 --> 35:25.055
in Pensacola, Florida.

35:25.057 --> 35:28.391
It recalls the daring pilot
who followed a glowing trail

35:28.393 --> 35:30.060
and finally found<i> Shangri-La.</i>

35:30.062 --> 35:31.594
♪♪

35:31.596 --> 35:37.267
Just outside Columbus, Ohio,
stand 109 six-foot-tall

35:37.269 --> 35:38.468
concrete ears of corn

35:38.470 --> 35:41.437
that seem to sprout
right out of the ground.

35:41.439 --> 35:42.872
Built in 1994,

35:42.874 --> 35:47.544
this oversized homage
to the area's agricultural past

35:47.546 --> 35:49.612
is known as Cornhenge.

35:49.614 --> 35:52.616
Just a few miles away,
in the city of Hilliard,

35:52.618 --> 35:54.384
is an institution
for those seeking

35:54.386 --> 35:56.219
a different field
of entertainment --

35:56.221 --> 35:59.822
the Early Television Museum.

35:59.824 --> 36:01.892
The collection
of vintage equipment

36:01.894 --> 36:07.397
includes a projection television
dating back to 1946,

36:07.399 --> 36:11.134
one of the first color sets
from 1954,

36:11.136 --> 36:14.704
and a studio camera
used during the 1960s.

36:14.706 --> 36:16.839
♪♪

36:16.841 --> 36:18.241
But one artifact

36:18.243 --> 36:21.111
recalls the story of the man
who started it all.

36:21.113 --> 36:23.880
The artifact is made
mostly out of wood.

36:23.882 --> 36:27.317
On the front is
a rectangular glass screen.

36:27.319 --> 36:30.320
Below this screen
are multiple white dials.

36:30.322 --> 36:32.388
It's more than 70 years old,

36:32.390 --> 36:35.058
and it was created
by a visionary.

36:35.060 --> 36:37.594
♪♪

36:37.596 --> 36:39.863
WILDMAN:
This groundbreaking TV

36:39.865 --> 36:43.867
set the stage for a revolution
that is still unfolding today.

36:43.869 --> 36:47.870
This is a story about an
underdog who didn't back down.

36:47.872 --> 36:51.141
♪♪

36:51.143 --> 36:53.009
WILDMAN:
It's the 1920s.

36:53.011 --> 36:56.779
The world is enthralled by
an incredible new invention --

36:56.781 --> 36:57.847
television.

36:57.849 --> 36:59.916
At the time, TV signals worked

36:59.918 --> 37:03.319
by shining light
through a rotating metal disk

37:03.321 --> 37:06.022
that breaks a picture
into pieces.

37:06.024 --> 37:08.091
The signal is sent along a wire

37:08.093 --> 37:10.226
or through the airwaves
to a lamp,

37:10.228 --> 37:12.095
and another rotating metal disk

37:12.097 --> 37:14.164
that puts the image
back together

37:14.166 --> 37:15.699
and displays it on a screen.

37:15.701 --> 37:18.701
The idea of transmitting
a picture over the air --

37:18.703 --> 37:22.038
that was novel, that was new,
and that was groundbreaking.

37:22.040 --> 37:23.539
♪♪

37:23.541 --> 37:26.175
WILDMAN:
But the technology is limited.

37:26.177 --> 37:29.679
The system relies entirely
on motorized mechanical parts

37:29.681 --> 37:32.382
that can only spin
up to a certain speed.

37:32.384 --> 37:36.318
The result is that the pictures
produced are poor in quality.

37:36.320 --> 37:39.389
It created images,
but they were never very clear.

37:39.391 --> 37:42.325
They always looked fuzzy
and a little bit off.

37:42.327 --> 37:46.262
WILDMAN: But one young man is
determined to fix this problem,

37:46.264 --> 37:49.799
a teenager named
Philo Farnsworth.

37:49.801 --> 37:52.201
PORGES:
Farnsworth was a country kid.

37:52.203 --> 37:53.737
He grew up in rural Idaho

37:53.739 --> 37:56.072
idolizing
the Edisons of the world

37:56.074 --> 37:59.342
who had created these inventions
that changed the world.

37:59.344 --> 38:02.211
WILDMAN: Farnsworth has
a passion for science,

38:02.213 --> 38:05.014
and he believes
he can improve image quality

38:05.016 --> 38:08.350
by eliminating a television's
mechanical parts entirely.

38:08.352 --> 38:12.656
For months, Farnsworth toils
away in his makeshift lab

38:12.658 --> 38:14.657
and eventually comes up
with a solution.

38:14.659 --> 38:18.328
The key is a special tube
that uses electricity

38:18.330 --> 38:23.199
to separate images line by line
and producing a sharper picture.

38:23.201 --> 38:25.301
He calls it an image dissector.

38:25.303 --> 38:29.238
This was the missing piece in
making a practical television,

38:29.240 --> 38:33.176
just the ability to transmit
this image at a fast enough rate

38:33.178 --> 38:35.712
that it would look like motion.

38:35.714 --> 38:40.049
WILDMAN: On September 7, 1927,
at the age of 21,

38:40.051 --> 38:43.386
Farnsworth tests
his new invention,

38:43.388 --> 38:45.989
and the picture
is astonishingly clear.

38:45.991 --> 38:48.291
PORGES:
This successful demonstration

38:48.293 --> 38:50.393
proved that
this image dissector worked.

38:50.395 --> 38:53.196
Farnsworth knew
he had something big.

38:53.198 --> 38:54.698
♪♪

38:54.700 --> 38:57.834
WILDMAN: But when the youthful
inventor files for a patent,

38:57.836 --> 38:59.536
he gets the shock of his life.

38:59.538 --> 39:03.740
An organization named the Radio
Corporation of America, or RCA,

39:03.742 --> 39:07.009
says Vladmir Zworykin,
one of their employees,

39:07.011 --> 39:09.479
came up with
the invention first.

39:09.481 --> 39:13.016
PORGES: It must have been
devastating to Farnsworth.

39:13.018 --> 39:15.685
This is basically every
inventor's worst nightmare.

39:15.687 --> 39:18.621
WILDMAN: So who will win
the battle of the box?

39:18.623 --> 39:19.789
♪♪

39:22.143 --> 39:23.142
♪♪

39:23.144 --> 39:26.512
It's the 1920s in San Francisco.

39:26.514 --> 39:28.815
A young man
named Philo Farnsworth

39:28.817 --> 39:30.617
has just invented a device

39:30.619 --> 39:33.420
that will transform
the way people watch TV,

39:33.422 --> 39:37.190
but when he files his patent,
the media giant RCA

39:37.192 --> 39:40.059
claims they've come up
with the idea first.

39:40.061 --> 39:44.264
So who will win this battle
of the boxes?

39:44.266 --> 39:47.933
Farnsworth believes
his invention is utterly unique

39:47.935 --> 39:49.569
and that there's no way

39:49.571 --> 39:51.404
RCA could have beaten him
to the punch.

39:51.406 --> 39:57.210
In fact, he's convinced
that RCA stole his concept.

39:57.212 --> 40:00.647
For years,
the two parties are embroiled

40:00.649 --> 40:04.684
in complex legal wrangling
until finally, in 1934,

40:04.686 --> 40:07.787
a piece of evidence surfaces
that will swing the case.

40:07.789 --> 40:10.389
Here was a lone inventor
going up against

40:10.391 --> 40:13.259
one of the largest
media companies in the world.

40:13.261 --> 40:15.662
This was a showdown,
David versus Goliath.

40:15.664 --> 40:17.263
♪♪

40:17.265 --> 40:20.200
WILDMAN: But Farnsworth
has a trick up his sleeve --

40:20.202 --> 40:22.869
his high-school
chemistry teacher.

40:22.871 --> 40:25.538
The man presents
as evidence a sketch

40:25.540 --> 40:28.274
Farnsworth drew
when he was just a boy.

40:28.276 --> 40:30.677
PORGES:
It turned out that Farnsworth

40:30.679 --> 40:33.713
had come up with the idea
for his image dissector

40:33.715 --> 40:35.548
when he was just 14 years old.

40:35.550 --> 40:39.052
He had shown a sketch
of this idea to his teacher,

40:39.054 --> 40:43.022
and his teacher brought
that sketch into the courtroom.

40:43.024 --> 40:45.291
WILDMAN:
The drawing demonstrates

40:45.293 --> 40:48.294
that Farnsworth had indeed
come up with the idea

40:48.296 --> 40:50.897
long before
RCA submitted their patent,

40:50.899 --> 40:52.599
and a court sides with him.

40:52.601 --> 40:55.401
PORGES: Farnsworth
must have been thrilled.

40:55.403 --> 40:58.471
He had put all of his passion,
all of his heart,

40:58.473 --> 41:00.907
all of his work
into this invention.

41:00.909 --> 41:01.908
♪♪

41:01.910 --> 41:04.844
WILDMAN:
Following the legal battle,

41:04.846 --> 41:09.248
RCA pays Farnsworth $1 million
to license his technology.

41:09.250 --> 41:12.718
Today, that's the equivalent
of $18 million,

41:12.720 --> 41:16.122
and by the mid-1950s,
televisions can be found

41:16.124 --> 41:18.591
in countless households
around the globe.

41:18.593 --> 41:22.128
We would not have modern TV as
we know it if it wasn't for him.

41:22.130 --> 41:24.464
Farnsworth was responsible
for inventing

41:24.466 --> 41:27.466
one of the most revolutionary
machines of the century.

41:27.468 --> 41:29.469
♪♪

41:29.471 --> 41:33.539
WILDMAN: Today, this 1940s set
created by Philo Farnsworth

41:33.541 --> 41:36.676
is on display at
the Early Television Museum

41:36.678 --> 41:38.044
in Hilliard, Ohio.

41:38.046 --> 41:42.582
It serves as a lasting reminder
of an underdog inventor

41:42.584 --> 41:46.552
who transmitted
a brand-new image of the world.

41:46.554 --> 41:51.090
From an ancient relic
to a beloved bunny,

41:51.092 --> 41:55.929
the invention of television
to an illuminating landing,

41:55.931 --> 42:00.433
I'm Don Wildman, and these are
the mysteries at the museum.
